'''Anthony Stephen Mathew''' (1734–1824<ref name = LondonSurvey/>) was a cleric the [[Church of England]]. He and his wife [[Harriet Mathew]] are most notable for their friendship and support of [[John Flaxman]] and [[William Blake]] and their gathering of intellectuals and artists salon in their house at [[Rathborne Place]]. Importantly, he was one of the original supporters of Blake's first collection of work ''[[Poetical Sketches]]'' (1783).<ref name = BlakeDict>{{cite dictionary |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=HOxpOMQ_Pa8C&pg=PA330| title = Poetical Sketches| work=A Blake Dictionary: The Ideas and Symbols of William Blake | pages= 330–331 |first= S. Foster |last= Damon| editor= Morris Eaves| publisher= [[University Press of New England]]| year= 1988| isbn =9780874514360}}</ref> Blake later satirised the Mathews, and the [[Joseph Johnson (publisher)#Johnson Circle and dinners|Johnson Circle]], in the collection ''[[An Island in the Moon]]''.<ref name="Bloom2003">{{cite book |last=Bloom |first=Harold |title= William Blake |series= ''Bloom's Major Poets'' |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=82Kt1HxLajQC&pg=PA13 |page=13 |accessdate= 16 November 2010 |year=2003 |publisher= Chelsea House Publications |isbn=0-7910-6812-9}}</ref>

==Career==
At the age of 17, Mathew entered the college [[Peterhouse, Cambridge|Peterhouse]] at [[Cambridge University]], subsequently entering the Church of England. Anthony Stephen Mathew was the first incumbent of [[Percy Chapel, Charlotte Street]], London starting in 1766 through 1804. He was succeeded by [[Thomas Beaseley]].Throughout his career in the church, he was rector of [[Glooston]], Leicestershire from 1781 and the [[Duke of Buccleuch]] gave him the rectorship of [[Broughton, Northamptonshire]] in 1790 which he held until he died. While in London, he was also a joint lecturer at [[St. Martin-in-the-Fields, London]].<ref name = LondonSurvey>{{cite book| work = Survey of London: volume 21: The parish of St Pancras part 3: Tottenham Court Road & neighbourhood| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=65155| pages = 13–26| editor = J. R. Howard Roberts and Walter H. Godfrey| title = Charlotte Street | year = 1949}}</ref><ref name =Williams>{{cite journal| title = An Identification of Some Early Drawings by John Flaxman| first = Iolo A.| last = Williams| journal = The Burlington Magazine| volume =102| number = 687 | date =June 1960| pages = 246–251| jstor = 873103}}</ref>

