{{Expand Italian|Baccanale degli Andrii|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file=Bacanal de los andrios.jpg | image_size=300px | title=The Bacchanal of the Andrians | artist=[[Titian]] | year = 1523–1526<ref name="prado"/> | medium=oil on canvas | height_metric=175 | width_metric=193 | city=[[Madrid]] | museum=[[Museo del Prado]] }} '''''The Bacchanal of the Andrians''''' is an oil painting by [[Titian]]. It is signed "<small>TICIANUS F</small>.[aciebat]" and is dated to 1523–1526.<ref name="prado">{{cite web|title=Enciclopedia online |url=http://www.museodelprado.es/enciclopedia/enciclopedia-on-line/voz/bacanal-de-los-andrios-la/?no_cache=1|work=Bacanal de los andrios|publisher=Museo del Prado|accessdate=2 December 2012|language=Spanish}}</ref>
The painting is now held at the [[Museo del Prado]] in [[Madrid]], but it was commissioned by [[Alfonso I d'Este, Duke of Ferrara|Alfonso I d'Este]] for his ''[[Camerini d'alabastro]]'' ('chambers of alabaster') in [[Ferrara]]. The decorative programme included other major paintings celebrating [[Bacchus]] and Venus, the gods of wine and love.
''The Bacchanal of the Andrians'' has been admired by other artists including Rubens who copied it.
