{{Infobox company |name = WestonWilliamson+Partners |type = Limited Liability Partnership |logo = |slogan = |foundation = |location = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] |locations = |key_people = |num_employees = 88 |revenue = |net_income = |industry = [[Architecture]] |homepage = [https://www.westonwilliamson.com/ www.westonwilliamson.com] }} [[File:WestonWilliamson+Partners Studio.jpeg|thumb|WestonWilliamson+Partners Studio [[Southwark]]]]
'''Weston Williamson''' is a British architectural firm formed in 1985 and based in [[London]] and Australia. [[Image:Lbplatform.jpg|thumb|right|2|The [[Jubilee line]] extension at [[London Bridge station]] (2007).]] [[File:Thames barrier park und dlr 02.02.2012 15-58-43.JPG|thumb|right|The new extension to the [[Docklands Light Railway]] from 2005.]]
==History== Weston Williamson was established in 1985 by Andrew Weston and Chris Williamson, who met whilst studying architecture. Weston and Williamson had also both studied with Steve Humphreys at [[Leicester Polytechnic]] School of Architecture, who joined the practice in 1991. In 2008 Rob Naybour became a fourth director.
In 2013 Weston Williamson became an LLP forming WestonWilliamson+Partners with the introduction of 9 new partners.
Weston Williamson + Partners has worked on a number of projects internationally including schemes for [[Transport for London]], [[Crossrail]], [[HS2]], the [[Docklands Light Railway]], the Dubai Transport Authority and the Malaysian Transport Authority. Other projects include the Oliver Morris House in [[Brixton]], New England Bio laboratories in [[Boston]] and the [[Jubilee line]] extension at [[London Bridge]].
==Projects== * Paddington Integrated Project<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transportbriefing.co.uk/news/story.php?id=6308|title=Transport Briefing subscriber log in|website=www.transportbriefing.co.uk}}</ref> * Docklands Light Railway Extension to London City Airport<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=3115985|title=Weston Williamson on how to get on board transport infrastructure projects|first=Katie|last=Puckett|publisher=}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=September 2017}} *Docklands Light Railway Extension to Woolwich<ref name=autogenerated1 />{{Dead link|date=September 2017}} *East London Line Stations at [[Hoxton railway station|Hoxton]] and [[Dalston Junction railway]] [[London Bridge station#Underground station|Jubilee line station]] at London Bridge<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{Citation|first=Brian |last=Edwards |title=The Modern Station: New Approaches to Railway Architecture |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cT1HAQAAQBAJ&pg=SA2-PA26&lpg=SA2-PA26&dq=%22Weston+Williamson%22&source=bl&ots=qq_C9bIW0e&sig=4SD1emchUItPrOn9FxehB1CTiIA&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ybw1VOagEsPN7QaYoIHwCA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22Weston%20Williamson%22&f=false |publisher= Taylor & Francis|year=1997|chapter=Part One:Perspectives on station architecture |ISBN=0-419-19680-3}} (electronic pages are unnumbered - see Suburban stations section "The Jubilee Line extension")</ref> * Paddington Crossrail<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=3154648|title=Paddington Crossrail images revealed|first=Ruth|last=Bloomfield|publisher=}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=September 2017}} *Miami Metromover<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdonline.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=3154451|title=Weston Williamson on track with Miami railway|publisher=}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=September 2017}} *HS2 Old Oak Common <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bdonline.co.uk/weston-williamson-lands-high-speed-2-station/5034856.article |title=Weston Williamson lands High Speed 2 s